name: Kempton Steam Museum
description: 1920s water pumping station comprising of several architectural styles. Interior retains original steam pumping machinery and historic electrical equipment.
address: Kempton Park Pumping Station, Snakey Lane, TW13 7ND

name: The Library at Willesden Green
description: A modern 4-storey building incorporating the much-loved Victorian library. The galleries and feature walls display exhibitions and contemporary art and a dramatic central atrium provides natural ventilation and daylight throughout.

name: Meridian Water Masterplan Tour
description: A unique site in the borough of Enfield. Meridian Water will be a distinctive neighbourhood designed to nurture economic, environmental and social sustainability. The tour provides an insight to the soon to be bold and unique development.
address: Meridian Water Station, Angel Edmonton Road, N18 3HF

name: Alton Estate
description: Alton Estate is renowned for its mix of high-rise Le Corbusian architecture in Alton West & its low-rise Scandinavian approach to modernism in Alton East. Designed by the London County Council  architects they completed in 1959.

name: St John at Hackney Church
description: St John at Hackney Church is the iconic Anglican parish church of Hackney, and has been a centre of Christian worship in the borough Since 1275. The present church was completed in 1792, with a major restoration completed in 2020.
address: St John at Hackney Church, Lower Clapton Road, E5 0PD

name: Canada Water Library
description: A civic centrepiece for the regeneration of the area around Canada Water. Its inverted pyramid form is an innovative response to providing an efficient single large library floor on a smaller footprint site.

name: Bow Church – St Mary
description: Medieval village church, restored in late 19C and after bomb damage in WWII. 15C font and memorials from five centuries. Grade II* listed. Refurbished for 700th anniversary in 2011; the bell tower and cupola were restored in 2017-18.

name: The Bower
description: Extending AHMM’s involvement in the regeneration of the Old Street area, The Bower reinvents a collection of underperforming buildings into a coherent mix of workspace, ground floor retail/restaurants and a new public realm.

name: The Old Library - Acton High Street
description: The red-brick property has an ornate façade facing Acton High Street.  It consists of two storeys with part third storey and is one of the historic civic buildings known as the Redbrick Quarter because of their distinctive appearance.

name: Enfield Chase Walk
description: The walk follows the London Loop footpath through Trent Park and along the Salmons Brook valley through the historical area of Enfield Chase, a former royal hunting forest.
address: Entrance on east side of Cockfosters Road, Enfield, EN4 0DZ

name: KnoxBhavan Studio
description: Every square inch of this former stationery shop has been maximised in its transformation into an innovative new studio for Knox Bhavan Architects. The studio is dedicated to the idea that workplace environment directly affects wellbeing.

name: Swakeleys Estate
description: A most important house in Ickenham an outstanding example of Jacobean architecture built in the 1630s. Red brick construction laid in English bond on an H plan. Great Hall includes the 1655 Harrington Screen, 18C marble fireplace panelling.
address: Swakeleys Road, Ickenham (access from Milton Road), UB10 8LD

name: National Youth Theatre
description: Completed in Summer 2021, the National Youth Theatre has been redeveloped to double its capacity for studio space and was designed with young people, for young people. Recipient of the Mayor of London's Good Growth Fund.

name: Wallington Library
description: Wallington library is the oldest library in Sutton borough, built in 1936. Designed by Robert Atkinson in the Neo-Georgian style, it bears the hallmarks of Art Decco design that was typical of the period.

name: Tooting Bec Lido
description: Outdoor pool 100x33 yards. One million gallons of unheated water. Iconic outdoor cubicle doors, fountain and café added in the 1930s, with Art Deco style entrance in 2001. Sports hall pavilion added in 2016.
address: Tooting Bec Lido, Tooting Bec Road, SW16 1RU

name: British Library
description: Highly acclaimed building of red brick with colourful window details and roof, the British Library is the ultimate in post-modernity. The design follows the English Free Style of architecture. RIBA Award Winner.

name: The Steamship Project Space
description: With a sculpture garden, performance art in the attic and live music in the bowels of The Steamship, built in the heart of Docklands 1885, the resident artists show how the area has transformed and how they've transformed the former pub.
address: The Steamship Project Space, 24 Naval Row, E14 9PS

name: Ealing Centre and North
description: Walk led by Ealing Civic Society members, Jenny Gadsby and Josette Bishop. The walk will cover Ealing north of Uxbridge Road. Circumstances permitting, it will include a tea stop in the garden of one of the walk leaders.
address: Haven Green opposite Ealing Broadway Station, The Broadway, Ealing, W5 2NU

name: Enfield Brewery
description: A modern open-plan building that houses fully-functioning and impressive brew house equipment. The exterior looks like a clean modern warehouse style building but the interior is updated with industrial equipment.

name: Poplar Works
description: A row of 80 semi derelict garages, has been converted and extended with a timber structure first floor, to provide a fashion hub, with public cafe, manufacturing space, start-up studios, education facility, and business units.

name: Skinner-Trevino House
description: A late Victorian house which has been almost completely gutted; now flooded with light by a new glass extension opening onto the semi-open plan ground level and a glass box extension into the roof.

name: Old Royal Naval College - King William Court
description: Wren-designed building completed under the direction of Hawksmoor and Vanbrugh, 1698-1712. Original wood panelling, refurbished by Dannatt Johnson in 2001 for University of Greenwich.
address: King William Court, 30 Park Row, SE10 9NN

name: Structuralist House
description: The project involved the extension and internal reconfiguration of a Victorian mid-terrace house in north London. The design of the four indoor and outdoor levels of the ground floor promotes interactions between inhabitants and visitors.

name: Medieval to Millennial
description: Join Blue Badge Guide Sue Grayson Ford to discover the treasures inside Enfield’s medieval parish church, and hear the stories behind many other listed buildings before visiting Enfield Chase and the New River, dating from 1613.

name: Hampstead House
description: Open City presents the film premier of Hampstead House, a renovation of a large Victorian property in Hampstead creating a luxurious and sophisticated family home.
address: Dominic McKenzie Architects, 81 Essex Road, N1 2SF

name: Kingston Historic walk
description:
We are  running our usual guided walking tours around historic Kingston this year with reduced numbers. The tour will be the same but fewer numbers will make it safer for all.
Our guided tours are informative, interesting and fun.
address: Market house, Kingston upon Thames, KT1 1JX

name: Bells and Belfries at St Botolph Aldgate
description:
Opportunity to hear a description and watch a demonstration of bell ringing (on Saturday only).
Church built by architect of Mansion House and contains London's oldest organ.
address: St Botolph's Church, Aldgate High Street, EC3N 1AB

name: Myddelton House
description: Former home of the great horticulturist Edward Augustus Bowles. Neoclassical yellow Suffolk stock brick villa. Victorian conservatory to south side. Mid-19C extension to north end. Adam style ceilings to ground floor.

name: The Royal Bell
description: The Royal Bell is a Grade II listed hotel that has lain empty for over ten years. Designed by Ernest Newton in 1898, it was one of three coaching inns in Bromley and an important centre of Victorian and Edwardian culture.

name: Bromley Little Theatre
description: Bromley Little Theatre (BLT) has an 113-seat auditorium that was originally a Victorian bakery and stables built in 1888. The  first production was in December 1937. Please wear masks in the building and observe social distancing.
address: Bromley Little Theatre, North St, (opposite Bromley North Station behind the Railway Tavern), Bromley, BR1 1SB

name: Valence Library
description: Single storey building, officially opened on 30th January 1937 and designed by the Borough’s Engineer & Surveyor F.C. Lloyd.
address: Valence Library, Becontree Avenue, Dagenham, RM8 3HT

name: Carreducker at 50 Chocolate Studios
description:
A Victorian chocolate factory conversion with exposed girders, brickwork and Crittal-style windows. 

No 50 was transformed from a flat into a traditional, bespoke shoemaking workshop, showroom and shoe & leather craft training school.

name: East Croydon Community Organisation
description: Find out just what Napoleon had to do with East Croydon and where DH Lawrence lived when he published his first novels. The East Croydon history walk will combine historical research with personal reminiscence.

name: St Mary The Virgin Wanstead
description: One of the finest examples of Georgian architecture. It has been hardly altered since built. The church is a rectangular building of Portland stone, with a projecting chancel. Two external walls were restored in 2019. Grade I listed
address: St Mary The Virgin Church, Overton Drive, E11 2LW

name: Kingston Edible Forest 2100
description: A mixed orchard of mostly perennial fruit and vegetables in a natural style to create a woodland and a delightful oasis.
address: Southern end of Knollmead Allotments, Knollmead, Tolworth, KT5 9QP

name: Havering Museum
description: A cultural centre in part of the old Romford Brewery building near to the historic market place. Permanent and temporary exhibition displays tell the story of the London Borough of Havering from Bronze Age to present day.

name: Ingrebourne Valley Visitor Centre
description: Ingrebourne Valley Visitor Centre, at Hornchurch Country Park, the Former RAF Hornchurch Airfield.
address: Hornchurch Country Park, Squadrons Approach, Hornchurch, RM12 6DF

name: Self-guided Architecture Walk - Putney Embankment
description: This walk takes you Thames-side, up to the Lower Richmond Road, back to the famous Boathouses and to the site of a pest house, all just 5 miles from Hyde Park Corner!

name: The Hurlingham Club
description: Bordering the Thames in Fulham, this 18th Century Georgian-style clubhouse is set in 42 acres of magnificent grounds. One of Britain’s greatest private members’ clubs, it retains its quintessentially English traditions and heritage.

name: Modern Architecture in Blackheath walk
description: Architect Ana Sutherland will lead a guided tour of the Cator Estate, covering Eric Lyons' Span estates and unique modernist homes designed by architects Patrick Gwynne, Peter Moro and Walter Greaves.

name: Wennington Parish Church of St Mary and St Peter
description: Grade II listed Norman church dating from as early as 1190 and as late as 1248.

name: Clitterhouse Farm
description: Our Yard at Clitterhouse Farm is a grassroots project working to protect historic Victorian farm outbuildings and transform the entire site into a vibrant and sustainable community hub. Shortlisted for the Open City Stewardship Awards 2021.
address: Clitterhouse Playing Fields, Claremont Rd, NW2 1AP

name: Sands End Arts and Community Centre
description: Designed to have a low environmental impact, the new community centre for the London Borough of H&F is a light & airy multi-purpose  scheme providing spaces for art exhibitions & community events with an ancillary café & dance studio.

name: Markfield Beam Engine and House
description:
A masterpiece of Victorian engineering, Markfield Beam Engine provided a vital public health facility from 1855-1964. 

Steaming demonstrations, 4 & 5 Sept from 12.30pm.

Set in Markfield Park along side the River Lee.
address: Markfield Park, Markfield Road, South Tottenham, N15 4RB

name: St Mary's Convent
description: Convent in 18C Grade II listed house, c1764-1792, with original features including fine decorative plasterwork. Various additions including west wing (1913-15), and harmonious care home facilities and chapel by PRP Architects (1998-2001).

name: Queen Elizabeth II Stadium
description: 2-storey concrete sports pavilion in streamlined 1930s style. Building work interrupted by WW2 and completed in 1952. Distinctive 'drum' contains stylised staircase leading to glass-walled café and sheltered seating.
address: Quen Elizabeth II Stadium, Donkey Lane, Enfield, EN1 3PL

name: The Temple Wanstead Park
description: The Temple, 1760 remnant of magnificent Wanstead House estate, set in Grade II listed landscape Wanstead Park. Displays within, activities for all under Doric portico & in grassed enclosure.

name: Wharf Road
description: Designed by architects Pollard Thomas Edwards, the £50m scheme delivered 98 new homes. 80 per cent of the homes are affordable including 64 for social rent. Wharf Road is set around two new communal gardens that face Regents canal.

name: Battersea's Hidden Parks
description: Walking tour introducing nine smaller local parks and public gardens, and revealing their history. Led by Clare Graham, Chair of the Society's Open Spaces Committee and author of 'Discovering Battersea's Open Spaces: a walking guide'.

name: Watermans
description: Watermans is a purpose-built combined arts centre comprising a 120-seat cinema, 239-seat theatre, gallery, studios and public spaces. It is brutalist in style in a stunning riverside location.

name: All Saints Church, Edmonton
description: Church dating back to at least early C12. Charles and Mary Lamb are buried in the churchyard.

name: Barking Riverside London
description: A new sustainable neighbourhood being created alongside 2km of south-facing Thames river frontage. A partnership with The Mayor of London and L&Q, 10,800 new homes will house up to 29,000 people.
address: The Wilds at Barking Riverside, Northgate Road, Barking, IG11 0AN

name: Pope's Grotto
description: Grotto with mineral decoration is last remaining part of Alexander Pope's villa built 1720. The villa was demolished 1808 and replaced and redeveloped many times in following years but Pope's Grotto remains.
address: Radnor House School, Pope's Villa, Cross Deep, Twickenham, TW1 4QG

name: Arcola Outside (Arcola Theatre)
description: Arcola Outside is a brand-new outdoor performance space and bar in the heart of Dalston, designed by multi-award-winning stage designer Jon Bausor. A flexible, multi-purpose space, for live performances, screenings, installations and more.

name: Oak Room, New River Head
description: Formerly boardroom of the 17C water house, the Oak Room is a fine late Renaissance room demonstrating the New River Company's wealth. 1697 carved oak interior, attributed to Grinling Gibbons, including overmantel and panels over the doors.
address: New River Head,, 173 Rosebery Avenue, EC1R 4UL

name: Hampstead Parish Church (St John-at-Hampstead)
description: The parish church is a focal point at the end of a row of attractive Georgian terraced houses.  The chapel-like exterior is deceiving and the beautiful interior with its high domed ceilings and beautiful stained glass windows is a surprise.

name: St Alphege Church, Edmonton
description: The Church of St Alphege is Grade II listed, combining modernist Scandinavian and traditional ecclesiastical forms with good-quality sculptural enrichment; graceful, lofty interiors, with subtle detailing applied consistently throughout.
address: Rossdale Drive/Hertford Road,, Lower Edmonton,, London,, N9 7LG

name: HM Treasury
description: Online only. A quadrangular, English Baroque revival building. Grade II* listed government office covering the entire complex, Great George Street constructed 1899-17 in two phases. Refurbishment completed 2002, now occupied by HM Treasury
address: Online only, 1 Horse Guards Road, SW1A 2HQ

name: Ebury Edge
description: Ebury Edge is a colourful temporary development, providing residents with a continuous community space as the Ebury Bridge Estate is re-developed in phases, together with affordable workspaces and a café.

name: West India Dock Impounding Station
description: The recently automated impounding station controls the water level in the docks using the original Worthington Simpson pumps driven by Lancashire dynamo.
address: Western end of Marsh Wall, E14 8JT

name: The Old Stables
description: Originally built as horses stables next to the Grand union Canal for a local brewery, it has been used to store barrage balloons and  various industrial uses over the years, currently used as an artist studio.
address: The Old Stables, Catherine Wheel Road, BRENTFORD, TW8 8BD

name: Bethlehem Chapel
description: An independent Calvinistic chapel on the east side of Church Terrace in Richmond, London. Built in 1797, the small 1-storey stuccoed building is Grade II* listed. It still has its original galleried interior with pews and pulpit.
address: Bethlehem Chapel, Church Terrace, Richmond upon Thames, TW10 6SE

name: The Clockworks
description: Internationally pre-eminent museum and integral workshops devoted to electrical timekeeping and the distribution of accurate time (1840-1970). Practical education and conservation in action.

name: 33 Genotin Road
description: Modern build concrete structure, glass exterior, 4 storeys plus a basement.  These are now totally used by Microsoft Ltd (previously Metaswitch Networks Ltd) as offices for up to 500 employees.

name: Working Men's College
description: Outstanding Edwardian building (1905 grade II; many original features). The oldest UK adult college, founded 1854 by FD Maurice, John Ruskin & Christian Socialists. Purpose-designed by WD Caroe; updated for modern educational aspirations.

name: Brook Green
description: We will explore a delightful oasis with Georgian houses, a Victorian church and a public girls’ school. The original brook still flows under the green. Brook Green has been home to actors,  artists' studios and a major national charity.
address: Brook Green Hotel, 170 Shepherds Bush Rd, Hammersmith,, W6 7PB

name: Reform Club
description: Built as a Whig gentleman's club and inspired by Italian Renaissance palaces. Lobby leads to an enclosed colonnaded courtyard with complementary glazed roof and tessellated floor. Tunnelled staircase leads to upper floor.

name: The Charterhouse
description: Founded as a Black Death burial ground, the site has served as a Carthusian monastery, Tudor mansion, school and an almshouse, which it remains to this day. The Charterhouse opened to the public in 2017 with a new museum.

name: Cody Dock
description: One of London's most exciting creative spaces, Cody Dock provides a gateway to the Lea River Park and is home to a gallery, gardens, cafe & bar that make this the perfect pit stop for exploring The Line Sculpture trail and Lower Lea River.

name: All Saints, Foots Cray
description: Medieval church (c1330) amended 1863 by Hakewill and retaining original elements such as windows and an arch to the north aisle, and altar tomb of Sir Simon de Vaughan.

name: St Barnabas Church
description: Early English style, full of Pre-Raphaelite decoration. Important works by Bodley, Comper and Cundy and windows by Kempe and Tower. First Oxford Movement church. Recently restored 10 bell peal; bell ringing quarter peal once a month

name: Garden Court Chambers
description: Inigo Jones design 1640 at 59/60 LIF, copied  by 57/58  with portico and elliptical staircase added by Soane.  Refurbished by current occupiers, a barristers' chambers. Retains many original features, staircases, fireplaces and mouldings

name: Salters' Hall
description: A rare example of a Brutalist Livery Hall which underwent extensive refurbishment in 2016. New Pavilion, exhibition and archive space and garden.

name: Boston Manor House and Park Walks
description:
Visitors will be shown around Boston Manor Park on short walks led by volunteers, focusing on the History of Boston Manor House and area.
The House is closed as part of a 5 year redevelopment project, re-opening early 2022.
address: Boston Manor House, Boston Manor Road, Brentford, TW8 9JX

name: Winchmore Hill Friends Meeting House & Burial Ground
description: Grade II listed, built 1790. A central double door under a bracketed cornice hood, large sash windows with delicate glazing bars. Panelled interior. Curved entrance wall allowed carriages to turn in the narrow lane. Notable burial ground.
address: Winchmore Hill Quaker Meeting House, 59 Church Hill, N21 1LE

name: East Dulwich Extension
description: A rear and side brickwork extension with pitched zinc roof with sliding doors and glazed courtyard separating new family kitchen from main house.  A simple tonal palette of pale brick, clay pavers and bespoke plywood cabinetry.

name: Golden Lane and Barbican Architecture Walking Tour
description: The walk, led by architectural historian Billy Reading, will explore the Golden Lane and Barbican estates, designed by architects Chamberlin, Powell & Bon and have witnessed a rollercoaster ride of changing public opinion over the decades

name: King's Cross Public Realm
description: King's Cross is a 67 acre development in Central London being transformed into a new city quarter with 20 regenerated heritage buildings, new homes, offices, public spaces, shops, galleries, bars, restaurants, schools and a university.
address: Western Transit Shed, 11 Stable Street, N1C 4AB

name: Tower Hamlets Cemetery Park
description: One of the magnificent 7 cemeteries. Burials ceased 1966, now 31 acres of woodland, meadows & ponds including the Soanes Centre (Robson Kelly 1993). Of outstanding importance for flora and fauna, set amongst funereal monuments, some listed
address: Soanes Centre. (On the right the main gates on Southern Grove), Mile End, E3 4PX

name: Christ Church
description: The church is designed in the Gothic style, with a semicircular barrel-vaulted ceiling, a highly carved chancel screen and magnificent stained glass windows, notably the large West window, depicting Christ the King enthroned in heaven.

name: Phoenix Gardens Community Building
description: The first purpose-built new-build community centre to be built in the heart of Soho for generations, located within the renowned Phoenix Gardens.

name: London Museum of Water & Steam
description: The Museum is housed within in a unique collection of Grade I and II listed buildings. Even though they were purpose-built and purely functional buildings, the architect took great care to make the buildings aesthetically pleasing.

name: The Ice House Quarter (featuring the Granary, Malthouse & Boathouse)
description: Home to the Granary and Malthouse, originally built for Randalls Malt Roasters c1860. The restored buildings include a Victorian Granary and adjacent Malthouse located on the River Roding/ Barking Creek.

name: Dalston Eastern Curve Garden
description: A vital community garden offering a model for maximum good for communities and for the environment on a small urban plot. It is now a site of Local Importance for Nature Conservation. Shortlisted for the Open City Stewardship Awards 2021.

name: Two Temple Place
description: By gothic revivalist architect, John Loughborough Pearson, and completed in 1895 for William Waldorf Astor as his estate office, the building overlooks the River Thames and embodies the outstanding workmanship of the late Victorian period.

name: The Ismaili Centre
description: Part of an international family of Ismaili Centres, a religious, cultural and social space for the Shia Ismaili Muslim community. The serenity of the entrance fountain to the roof garden reflects Muslim traditions in architecture and design

name: Little Holland House (online only)
description: Closed for refurbishment. Grade II listed building inspired by the ideals of John Ruskin and William Morris and contains Dickinson's paintings, hand-made furniture, furnishings, metalwork and friezes, in Arts & Crafts style.

name: St. Margaret's House
description: St. Margaret's House is a group of buildings centred around a 3-storey Georgian terrace. Victorian additions were made in the building of a Chapel (consecrated 1904) and Mulberry Rooms. The buildings host several community projects.

name: Museum of Neoliberalism
description: The museum is situated in a shopfront in Leegate Shopping Centre, which has been described by the Evening Standard as "the worst shopping precinct in the country."

name: Canada House
description: Canada's diplomatic home in the United Kingdom, the revitalised Canada House serves as a showcase for the very best of Canadian art and design in the 21C.

name: Westminster Quaker Meeting House
description: Opened in 1883, with front doors added in the 1920s. It was bomb-damaged in 1941 and rebuilt in 1956. Grade II listed registered place of worship, it contains a peaceful meeting room and 1950s wood panelling and fittings.

name: Bookend House
description: A modest modern timber extension and refurbishment rationalizing internal spaces and adding an external staircase to connect outdoor spaces, located within the Stroud Green Conservation Area.

name: The Cartoon Museum
description: Underground museum. Interior design by Sam Jacobs Studio. Design concept influenced by cartoon and comic narrative techniques.
address: The Cartoon Museum, 63 Wells St, W1A 3AE

name: Parish Church of St Andrew Enfield
description: Listed church, much added to, with a recently refurbished organ which has a fine circa 1750s wooden organ case. There are many fine memorials. The Church has an eight-bell peal – the oldest bell dates from 1680.
address: The Market Place, Church Street, Enfield, EN2 6LL

name: Coombe Conduit
description: Coombe Conduit is one of Kingston’s most important ancient monuments. It was built around 1540 as part of a system to collect fresh water from springs on Kingston Hill and channel it to  Hampton Court Palace.
address: Coombe Lane West, Kingston upon Thames, KT2 7HF

name: The Library House
description: Designed by award-winning Macdonald Wright Architects and built in 2020, this two bed, two floor terraced home combines exceptional thermal efficiency, a solar array, exquisitely crafted materials and a secluded walled garden to the rear.
address: The Library House, 211 Northwold Road, E5 8RA

name: Whitewebbs Museum of Transport
description:
Victorian Pumping station built for the New River Company. When 
 converted to a museum the well, original iron roof bracing, hand operated crane,  weighbridge and many of the splendid Victorian details of the design were retained.

name: Honeywood Museum
description: Chalk and flint house dating to 17C with additions including extensions of 1896 and 1903 when owned by John Pattinson Kirk. Rich in period detail and the interior restored and stairs opened up with funding from the Heritage Lottery Fund.

name: Granary Square Pavilion
description: Granary Square Pavilion is a pavilion incorporating a retail unit, public WCs and public access lift. The pavilion has a decorative cast iron façade that extends up to form a balustrade to Granary Square.
address: Unit 119A  Lower Stable Street, Coal Drops Yard, Kings Cross, N1C 4DQ

name: St Pancras Church & Crypt
description: Unique Greek-style parish church. Grade I listed building inspired by the ionic temple of the Erechtheum on the Acropolis. A notable feature are the Caryatids guarding the entrances to the crypt.
address: Euston Road/Upper Woburn Place NW1, NW1 2BA

name: Hinde Street Methodist Church
description:
The chapel building is the second on the site, dating from 1887, and the most impressive of the designs of Weslyan Methodist architect, James Weir.
The interior is very attractive,  with a gallery around three sides and a high pulpit.

name: Marylebone Village: Home to The Howard de Walden Estate
description: This fun and engaging walking tour led by expert guide Mike Althorpe - an urban historian, architectural researcher, educator and story teller - will explore the architecture and history of this urban village.

name: Roca London Gallery
description: A unique space where water acts as the architectural theme - offering an innovative and interactive experience with Roca, the global bathroom brand.

name: Dreamings collage art exhibition
description: A collage art exhibition. Every day except Monday and Tuesday. A talk "Why Collage?" on Sunday evening at 7, followed by a Q&A and an art raffle for charity
address: The Brook Pub, 38 New Rd, Brentford TW8 0NU, TW8 0NU

name: Christ Church Southgate and the Minchenden Oak Garden
description: Grade II listed church with fine collection of Pre-Raphaelite stained glass windows by Morris & Co. including Burne Jones and Rossetti. Wall paintings. Mosaic reredos. Minchenden Oak  - ancient pollarded oak more than 800 years old.

name: City Information Centre
description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. This subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's. RIBA Award Winner 2009.

name: Hermitage Community Moorings
description: A development of residential and recreational moorings for historic vessels on the Thames. The unique Pier House, built to a high specification, provides a floating community centre just downstream from Tower Bridge.

name: Drapers' Hall
description: Livery hall first built in the 1530s, twice destroyed by fire and rebuilt (1666 & 1772). Late 19C facade and opulent Victorian interior.

name: Polish Social and Cultural Association
description: Built 1971-74 in brutalist style. The largest Polish centre in Western Europe, it contains a theatre, the Polish Library, the Polish University Abroad, a Joseph Conrad collection, Jazz Café, art gallery and art collection on public display.

name: Brockley 3 Peaks Walk
description: A circular 5 mile walk, mainly through parkland with beautiful views across London from the 3 peaks – Hilly Fields, Blythe Hill Fields and One Tree Hill.  The walk is easy to moderately difficult. One Tree Hill is not wheelchair friendly.
address: Pistachios in the Park, Hilly Fields, Brockley, SE4 1LB

name: Manor House Gardens Ice House
description: Grade II listed ice well and underground chambers (1770) in Manor House Gardens park, which provided ice for nearby Manor House. Cited in 2002 Civic Trust Awards.

name: St Martin's Parish Church, West Drayton
description:
A Grade II* listed church dating from 13th century with some interesting features
Adjacent to a 16th century Gate House

name: Open City Film: Core Landscapes
description: A community garden space teaching horticultural skills to promote positive wellbeing. Part of a 3 part series, exploring the role of wellbeing and architecture around East London kindly supported by Allies & Morrison

name: New Ground (online only)
description: 25 homes designed with the Older Women’s Co-Housing group using PTE’s ‘fabric first’ approach which maximises the benefits of orientation, air-tightness and insulation and following the co-housing model.
address: 5b Union Street, Chipping Barnet, Barnet, London, EN5 4DF

name: Points of view: Understanding London’s townscape
description: Following architect Gordon Cullen’s ideas of townscape and concentrating on postwar commercial development in the City of London, explore the aesthetic and legislative background to buildings, streets and spaces close to St Paul’s Cathedral

name: Benjamin Franklin House
description: Grade I listed Georgian house, the only surviving home of Benjamin Franklin, retaining many original features including central staircase, lathing, 18th Century panelling, stoves, windows, fittings and beams.

name: The Art Workers' Guild
description: 1713 terraced house with 1914 hall at rear. Notable renovated Arts and Crafts interior. Newly refurbished glass vaulted courtyard. Portraits of Guild Masters since 1884.

name: Goldfinger, Trellick Tower
description: Goldfinger is a social enterprise situated at the foot of the Grade II listed Trellick Tower. We craft bespoke furniture from reclaimed and sustainable materials, with a teaching academy for the local community.

name: King George V Pumping Station
description: Designed to pump water from the River Lee into the King George V reservoir, the building houses three old disused gas Humphrey pumps, and two electric pumps currently in service.

name: Brentham Garden Suburb
description: Britain's first co-partnership garden suburb, first houses built 1901. Parker and Unwin's plan introduced 1907, mainly Arts and Crafts style; fascinating social history.
address: The Brentham Club, 38 Meadvale Road, W5 1NP

name: Grand Junction at St Mary Magdalene Church, Paddington
description: Grade I Victorian Gothic church by G E Street, architect of the Royal Courts of Justice. The recent conservation project reveals the majestic colours of Daniel Bell's painted ceiling, plus Dow Jones Architects' contemporary heritage wing.
address: Rowington Close, St Mary Magdalene's Church, W2 5TF

name: St Alban Church
description: Notable 1930s Grade II listed church with Swedish and German influences externally. Landmark tower. Stepped tunnel-vault with arches to side aisle walls giving a light lively interior. Marquetry panelling to Lady Chapel.

name: The Swedenborg Society
description: Grade II listed Georgian domestic building c1760, formerly part of Bedford Estate. Interior refurbished 1924-5 to form lecture hall (restored 2014), library, bookshop and offices. Oak woodwork and green Doulton tiles line the staircase.

name: St Augustine's Tower
description: Grade I listed, remaining tower of medieval parish church, with working late 16C clock. New exhibition of Hackney's history. Extensive views from roof. (Organised by Hackney Historic Buildings Trust).

name: Culture at risk: Crystal Palace Park – a tour with a London Blue Badge Tourist Guide
description:
Explore the world's first dinosaur models hidden in a south London park. The 30 Grade I listed, life-size statues of dinosaurs and other extinct animals at Crystal Palace Park have thrilled
visitors for 166 years. Tour is kids friendly.
address: Crystal Palace Park, Meeting point is Crystal Palace Overground/National Rail station, SE19 2AZ

name: Pitzhanger Manor & Gallery
description: Designed by Sir John Soane as a family home and country residence. Following a three-year conservation project,  Pitzhanger has been returned to Soane’s innovative original design and re-opened to the public in March 2019.

name: Reliance Arcade
description: Reliance Arcade is a Grade II Listed covered market in Brixton, London.  The Arcade was constructed in the 1920s and is home to 40 small retail units catering largely to local African-Caribbean communities.

name: St Benet Fink Church
description: J S Alder's most complete and unaltered church, at the church's consecration in 1912 it was referred to as 'the little Cathedral' thanks to its light and airy Gothic design.

name: Hammersmith Library
description: Fine Carnegie-funded Edwardian library (1905). First floor Ionic colonnade flanked by end pavilions, large Baroque doorway, and glazed barrel-vaults. 16/17C stained and painted Dutch glass  and statues of Shakespeare and Milton on exterior.

name: Aga Khan Centre
description: The Aga Khan Centre, designed by Pritzker prize winning architect Fumihiko Maki, houses the UK institutions of the Aga Khan Development Network. A unique feature are its six gardens inspired by different regions of the Muslim world.
address: Aga Khan Centre, 10 Handyside Street, N1C 4DN

name: St Bernard's Houses
description: 21 houses, in 3 terraces, built by Swiss architects Atelier 5 for Wates. Living areas on the upper floor are approached through a garden court. Bedrooms downstairs open to a lower garden. Pevsner wrote, 'a group with few equals in Britain'.
address: Meet: by OH banner, St Bernard's, Chichester Road, Croydon, CR0 5UL

name: Highgate School Chapel, Library, Museum
description: Highgate is three schools in one. Founded by Sir Roger Cholmeley, Lord Chief Justice of England, in 1565, Highgate is governed as a single charitable foundation.

name: Eco House
description:
ONLINE ONLY.

A Georgian fronted terrace house, remodelled in 2016 to create an 'L' shaped modern eco house. Open and private living spaces designed horizontally across the ground floor, quiet relaxation spaces designed vertically.

name: Secret Belgravia
description: A peaceful area of Central London that began as 100 acres of marshy land, and became homes to the royal, rich and famous, and of course scandal and intrigue. A beautiful area of London with so many secrets.

name: Bluebell Centre, Perivale Wood Nature Reserve
description: The low carbon building is a straw bale construction built on compacted tyres with a cedar roof.  In the Perivale Nature Reserve owned by the Selborne Society it is used for society meeting and as an education centre for adults and schools.

name: Bruce Castle Museum
description: Tudor Manor House built for Sir William Compton in 1514, substantially altered in 17C, 18C & 19C. A museum since 1906 housing local history and community collections, archives, art & exhibitions of Bruce Castle, and Haringey area.
address: Bruce Castle Museum,, Lordship Lane, Tottenham, N17 8NU

name: Walthamstow Pumphouse Museum
description: Grade II listed Victorian engine house remodelled to take a pair of 1895 Marshall steam engines, still in working order. A museum celebrating the rich Boroughs and the Lea Valley Region Industrial Heritage.

name: Open City Film: The Lea Navigation Canal
description: Follows one of the most socially, architecturally and historically diverse parts of London. Part of a 3 part series, exploring the role of wellbeing and architecture around East London kindly supported by Allies & Morrison.

name: Blackbook Winery
description: Blackbook Winery is in a converted Victorian railway arch.  It is open plan, with all equipment required to process, ferment and age wine on site – press, tanks, barrels etc.  Our grapes come from English growers within 2 hours of London.
address: Arch 41, London Stone Business Estate, Broughton Street, SW8 3QR

name: Whitehall Historic House
description: Originally a farmer's house dating to 1500, with jettied upper storey. Later additions reflect the changing lifestyles of the owners, including the Killicks for over two centuries. Now houses scale model of Henry VIII's Nonsuch Palace.

name: GARDEN OF EARTHLY DELIGHTS🌱🐝🍅🦋
description: The Garden of Earthly Delights is a community garden and a "meanwhile" space to raise awareness of empty spaces in the city, grow food for the local community and increase biodiversity. We hold workshops and events to which all are welcome.

name: Nunhead Cemetery
description: Magnificent Victorian cemetery with Gothic chapel & restored & ruined lodge. One of London's wildest cemeteries. Part restored with the help of a lottery grant. 52 acres of woodland, with bats, owls, foxes & squirrels. Grade II* landscape.

name: Union Chapel
description: Online only. An architectural Grade I treasure that’s home to an inclusive church, an award winning venue, a unique organ and The Margins Project for those homeless and in crisis in London.

name: The City Churches: St Mary Aldermary
description:
Guild Church, first mentioned c1080. Oldest of the City churches dedicated to St Mary. Only Wren church built after the Great Fire, courtesy of a bequest, in late Gothic style.  
Please wear masks and use the hand sanitizer at the door.

name: Croydon Minster
description: Medieval style church rebuilt by Sir George Gilbert Scott after 1867 fire. Tower & south porch are 15C. Large nave with open timber-work roof leads to chancel dominated by superb stained glass window & rich alabaster reredos.

name: Royal Opera House
description: Housing the Royal Opera and the Royal Ballet, the historic building was reconfigured in 2018 by Stanton Williams to deliver not only world-class performance spaces, but also a welcoming and inclusive cultural and social hub.

name: Cool East London Heats Up: Arts Under Pressure
description: In post-Olympic E. London, Hackney Wick had Europe's densest concentration of artists. Now studios & arts spaces struggle to survive gentrification. On these walks we'll visit key cultural locations, meeting those trying to preserve them.

name: Ss Peter & Paul Church
description:
Nave (1844) by Lewis Vulliamy, chancel (1903) by Sir Arthur Blomfield. Stained glass windows by Christopher Webb and 
by Clayton & Bell. Norman font brought from the Old Church. Grade II* listed.

name: The Hospital Chapel of St Mary & St Thomas
description: Founded c1145 by the Abbess of Barking as a hospice for thirteen old and infirm men, the present building is 12C and 19C. Grade II* listed with many interesting monuments, including Burne-Jones windows.

name: The Church of Our Most Holy Redeemer
description: A unique II* listed Italianate church by John Dando Sedding with attached Campanile and Institute Building. Of particular significance in the church is the imposing baldacchino over the High Altar, which dominates the east end.

name: Pushkin House
description: A centre of Russian culture in London, this Grade II* listed Georgian townhouse has a fine staircase which has been meticulously restored, and a large reception room for music salons.

name: Creative Mile: Brentford Art Trail
description: A celebration of Brentford's creativity, its industrial past, and it's riverside communities, with artist studios and pop-up exhibitions spread across 8 venues along a one-mile walking route running from Kew Bridge down to Johnson's Island.

name: Old Royal Naval College - Queen Mary Court
description: Last major building on the site (1751). Original layout, timber panelling, barrel vaulting and Portland stone. Refurbished in 2000 by Dannatt Johnson for University of Greenwich.
address: Queen Mary Court, 30 Park Row, SE10 9NN

name: Trinity Buoy Wharf/Container City
description: Home to London's only lighthouse, fine stock buildings and examples of the innovative Container City buildings. This former buoy manufacturing site is now a centre for the creative industries with various sculptures and installations.

name: The Stanley Picker Trust, Picker House (online only)
description: Completed in 1968 by Kenneth Wood, RIBA, T Eng (CEI).  A time capsule of the 1960s, it is set in a quiet cul-de-sac on steeply sloping ground which both inspired and challenged the architect when creating the modern split-level design.

name: Devonport Mausoleum
description: Beautiful mausoleum in former Royal Navy cemetery, restored 1999 by the University of Greenwich. Many interesting plaques and grave stones.
address: National Maritime Museum, Romney Road, SE10 9NF

name: Hampstead Garden Suburb Free Church
description: Grade I listed Non-conformist church, set in the suburb's integrally planned Central Square to balance St Jude's Church nearby, but with a low concrete dome. Distinctive interior with large Tuscan columns on high brick plinths.
address: Central Square, hampstead Garden Suburb, NW11 7AG

name: Hornchurch House
description: Newly built contemporary homes designed to be sensitive to their surroundings.

name: Barts Pathology Museum, Queen Mary University of London
description: Barts Pathology Museum is based in the grounds of St Bartholomews Hospital at West Smithfield and houses over 4,000 medical specimens on display over 3 mezzanine levels of the Victorian museum.
address: 3rd Floor Robin Brook Centre, St Bartholomew's Hospital, West Smithfield, EC1A 7BE

name: Alderman Jones House
description: Becontree Estate two storey cottage house with garden located on a banjo.

name: Moravian Close
description: A former stable yard of Sir Thomas More's Chelsea estate, now an 18C Chapel, other buildings, and burial ground. Parts of the enclosing walls are Tudor in origin. Ernest and Mary Gillick enhanced the grounds in the 20C.

name: 38 Grosvenor Square
description: A beautiful Mayfair town house c 1727 original to the Square. Transformed 1776 by John Johnson for Duke of Dorset; magnificent staircase, lavish ‘Adamesque’ entertaining suite. Mid-C19 Italianate front by Thomas Cundy.

name: The Royal Parks Kiosks
description: A public realm enhancement project across London's Central Royal Parks, including a new landmark café overlooking The Serpentine Lake and nine sculptural "handcrafted" refreshment kiosks.
address: The Serpentine Coffee House, West Carriage Drive, Hyde Park, W2 2UH

name: Brentford & Isleworth Quaker Meeting House
description: Grade II* listed late-Georgian Quaker Meeting House (1785) set in garden with burial ground. Meeting room has wood panelling, elders' bench, upper gallery with drop shutters, and fine brickwork detailing. Contemporary brick boundary wall.
address: Quakers Lane, London Road, Isleworth, TW7 5AZ

name: Freemasons' Hall
description: Monumental Art Deco exterior belying elaborate and varied interior decoration: extensive use of mosaic, stained glass, decorated ceilings and lighting.
address: Freemasons' Hall, 60 Great Queen Street, WC2B 5AZ

name: 23 Sedgeford Road
description: Completely carbon neutral terraced house following a retrofit solar and air source heat pump installation. Existing radiators, double glazing and roof / loft insulation.

name: Holy Trinity Church in Bow
description: Holy Trinity Bow, a Grade C listed Church and graveyard built between 1834 and 1841 lies within the Tredegar Square Conservation Area on a site gifted by the developer of Tredegar Square, Sir Charles Morgan.

name: Bloom Clerkenwell
description: Bloom Clerkenwell is a wellness focused, new office for developer HB Reavis. With roof terraces, an in-house gym and retail, it is situated over the new  Farringdon Crossrail station and has outstanding links with the city and beyond.

name: Royal Pharmaceutical Society Museum
description: The RPS museum collections cover all aspects of British pharmacy history, from the 1400s up to the present day. The library's early printed collection includes pharmaceutical texts dating back to 1485.

name: Centre of the Cell and Neuron Pod, Queen Mary University of London
description: Neuron Pod is a striking 23-metre long and 10-metre high free-standing structure – designed as an extension to Centre of the Cell, an informal science learning centre at Queen Mary University of London’s Whitechapel campus.

name: Kingswood House  (online only)
description: Grade II listed building. Substantial villa built in form of stone-faced baronial castle for the inventor of Bovril. Now contains a library and community centre.

name: Hyde Park Chapel
description: The four-story Church façade and prominent seven-story tower is covered in Portland stone and highlighted by a golden steeple. The interior features the Christus statue and a large mural of the resurrected Jesus Christ.

name: Brockley's Historic Mews
description: Brockley Conservation Area's quirky mews are a mixture of leafy lanes and industrial units, with Victorian and interesting modern architecture existing in harmony. The cherished public right of way  allows community contact with nature.
address: Ashby, Wickham, Breakspears Mews, Junctions with Ashby Road, SE4 1TF

name: Page High Estate
description: Page High is a hidden jewel of post-war London social housing, a 92-home rooftop village in Wood Green. High above the hue and cry of the High Road, Page High (Good Design in Housing award, 1976) is a model for social housing today.

name: Olympic Legacy Masterplan
description: London’s 2012 Games provided a catalyst for regeneration in the Lower Lea Valley. Guided by the Legacy Masterplan, thousands of new homes and jobs are now being created, stitching together existing communities across the former floodplain.

name: Heath Robinson Museum
description: This NLHF supported, accredited, purpose-built museum in Pinner Memorial Park displays a collection of Heath Robinson’s work. It includes permanent & temporary exhibition galleries, activity space & shop. It was designed by ZMMA.
address: Pinner Memorial Park, West End Lane, Pinner, HA5 1AE

name: St Barnabas' Church and Mission Hall
description: Early 20th C Grade II* listed church designed by CH Reilly. Byzantine in structure but prefiguring Modernism in its aesthetic, Nairn judged it “the best church of its date in London”, Reilly “the building I should like to be remembered by”.
address: St Barnabas' Church, Shackewell Row, E8 2EA

name: DLR Underline Discovery Sessions
description: DLR Underline Discovery Sessions covers a series of events for all ages focused on exploring the spaces under the DLR on the Isle of Dogs, with activities exploring the area's architecture, heritage and the public realm.
address: DLR Underline - Isle of Dogs, From Crossharbour DLR Station to South Dock, E14 3BQ

name: University of Greenwich, Stockwell Street
description: The building features a limestone exterior designed to 'complement but not mimic' the surrounding historical architecture, whilst behind the façade is a 4-storey composition of steel, glass and exposed concrete.

name: Isokon Building (Lawn Road Flats)
description: Grade I listed 1934 residential block of flats in Hampstead, designed by the Canadian modernist architect Wells Coates for clients Jack and Molly Pritchard. English Heritage blue plaque for Bauhaus masters Gropius, Breuer and Moholy-Nagy.

name: St Pancras Chambers and Clock Tower
description: Former Midland Grand Hotel, now St Pancras Renaissance Hotel and Chambers apartments. Includes hotel lobby and clock tower.
address: The Forecourt, St Pancras Station, Euston Road, NW1 2AR

name: Putting the Park in Wembley Park: an exclusive preview of Wembley Park's emerging Union Park and botanical tour of the neighbourhood's green spaces.
description: Quintain, the award-winning team behind the £3bn regeneration of Wembley Park, will host a series of guided tours of Wembley Park's emerging 7-acre Union Park and other new green spaces across the neighbourhood.
address: Olympic Steps, Olympic Way, Wembley Park, HA9 0NP

name: Self-guided Architecture Walk - Upper Richmond Road westwards
description: From Putney Cross to Putney Park Lane, this self guided walk includes a wealth of significant buildings in a variety of uses past and present, churches, pubs, even the site of WWII bomb damage.

name: Surbiton Queen of the Suburbs
description: Join us for an interesting and informative walk around Surbiton with our experienced guide. Find out why Surbiton was called the Queen of the suburbs and plenty more.

name: Southwark Integrated Waste Management Facility
description: One of Europe's most advanced recycling facilities, comprising many sustainable features including grey water, solar panels and a green roof. Designed for the purpose of turning waste into a resource.
address: 43 Devon Street, (off Old Kent Road), SE15 1AL

name: Greenwich Yacht Club
description: Contemporary timber and aluminium building using existing pier, offering unique views of the river, the O2 and the Thames Barrier.

name: Hogarth's House
description: Early 18C red brick home of artist William Hogarth extended significantly c1749-1764. A 2020 extension adds a curved glass wall in the shape of Hogarth's Line of Beauty. Delightful walled garden containing famous ancient mulberry tree.
address: Hogarth Lane, Great West Road, W4 2QN

name: 1 Finsbury Avenue
description: 1 Finsbury Avenue is a Grade II listed building constructed in the early 1980s by Arup Associates (Peter Foggo). As the first building in the Broadgate development it was significant in defining the speculative office typology in London.

name: A tour of Victorian Bromley
description: A virtual tour that tells the story of Bromley's phenomenal growth in the late 19thC using many Victorian photos to fade in over the modern view to show how the town progressed from a rural market town to suburb in about 20 yrs.
address: East St, North St, High Street, Bromley, BR1 1NN

name: Kaymet Factory
description: The operational factory of Kaymet, a maker of trays and trolleys since 1947. A hidden 1950s building with a small yard, originally a printing works. It is brick built, with clear-storey glazing and tubular truss north-light main shed roof.

name: Orleans House Gallery
description: Louis Philippe, Duc d'Orleans, lived here between 1815-17. Gibbs' Baroque Octagon Room and adjoining gallery/19C stable block are the remaining parts of Orleans House. The Octagon Room was restored in 2018. Contemporary art gallery.

name: Centre Building: London School of Economics
description: Completed in May 2019, LSE's Centre Building is a state of the art flexible and highly sustainable academic and teaching building, designed by renowned architects Roger Stirk Harbour + Partners.
address: London School of Economics & Political Science, 2 Houghton Street, WC2A 2AD

name: Birbeck College 373 Euston Road
description: The refurbishment and roof extension of 7-storey building at 373 Euston Road to accommodates a 180-person lecture theatre, high-quality classrooms, as well as formal and informal co-learning spaces.

name: Royal Over-Seas League
description: Over-Seas House is an amalgamation of two Grade I listed buildings – Rutland House (James Gibbs, 1736) and Vernon House (1835 rebuilt 1905), with an Art Deco style wing added in 1937.
address: Park Place, St James's Street, SW1A 1LR

name: South London Gallery
description: Public contemporary art gallery housed in 3 listed Victorian buildings restored by 6a architects. Comprising galleries, café, shop, gardens, kitchen and converted Victorian Fire Station.

name: St James the Less Church
description: One of London's best Victorian churches and a key building in the history of the Gothic Revival. Polychromatic brickwork, with internal art work by G.F. Watts and Thomas Earp, windows and painted ceiling by Clayton and Bell. Grade I listed.
address: Thorndike Street,, off Moreton Street, SW1V 2PS

name: Enfield To Fork - Edmonton Green Shopping Centre
description: The Museum of Enfield is this year bringing its temporary exhibition to you! “From Enfield to Fork” explores the borough’s history and relationship with food, from Roman Enfield to Market Gardening.

name: Core Kensington
description: A Pilates studio like no other. The design combines functionality with creative and beautiful solutions. Influenced by the Norwegian-Mexican background of the owners, full of bespoke elements and details. The result is warm and minimal.
address: Bridgeman House, 375 Kensington High Street, W14 8AZ

name: RIBA
description: Fine example of Grade II* listed 1930s architecture with many original features and fittings and home to the world-class British Architectural Library collections. Open for pre-book visits only.

name: St Andrew's Kingsbury (new church)
description: Meticulous 1930s rebuilding (complete with original furnishings) of an 1840s Marylebone church. Grade I listed. Contains works by Pugin, Burges, Street, Pearson and Butterfield.
address: junction of Church Lane/Tudor Gardens/ Old Church Lane, Kingsbury, NW9 8RZ

name: House on the End
description: Replacing unused garages, this end-of-terrace, infill site development is a contemporary reinterpretation of the neighbouring terraces, complementing the streetscape and adding a House on the End.

name: New Scotland Yard
description: The Met Police’s home on the Embankment, created from the 1930s Curtis Green building with a new curved glass pavilion entrance and extensions to the rooftop and rear. Winner of the 2017 Prime Minister’s Better Public Building Award.

name: Baitul Futuh Mosque
description: Largest purpose-built mosque in Western Europe accommodating 13,000 worshippers. The building is a blend of Islamic and modern British architecture and incorporates much of the structure of an old dairy site.
address: Ahmadiyya Muslim Association, 181 London Road, Morden, SM4 5PT

name: Yorkton Workshops
description: Pearson Lloyd have transformed a series of dilapidated workshop buildings into a new home for the studio. Original features have been retained and, wherever possible, the building’s constituent materials have been reused and recycled.

name: St George's Bloomsbury
description: St George's Bloomsbury is one of the twelve new churches designed and paid for under the 1711 Act of Parliament for building fifty new Churches, and the sixth and final London Church designed by Hawksmoor.

name: St Mary the Virgin
description: Small Grade I listed 12C chapel in lovely churchyard setting, it retains original architectural features and has interesting brasses, monuments and stained glass windows.
address: Church Road, Manor Park, Little Ilford, E12 6HA

name: St Dunstan and All Saints Church
description: Grade I listed early medieval parish church (from 952 before Tower of London) in spacious churchyard. Fine interior: Anglo-Saxon Rood, Norman font, 'squint', fine memorials incl founders of Trinity House, 1950s glass. Bells of Stepney.

name: Self-guided Architecture Walk - Putney High Street to the River Wandle
description: This walk (approx 1 mile) takes you from St Mary’s Church along commercial and residential developments on the south bank of the Thames and through Wandsworth Park ending at the mouth of the River Wandle.

name: Christ Church
description: Grade II* listed church with ragstone tower, spire, good stained glass by Kempe and recently restored William Hill organ. A characteristic work of Scott. It is Gothic Revival in the style of the 13C.

name: Embassy of the Republic of Poland
description: Georgian townhouse built by Robert and James Adam in the years 1776-1780 is a fine example of the Adam style of Neoclassical interior design. Seat of the Polish Embassy in London since 1921, it also houses a collection of Polish artworks.

name: German Historical Institute
description: This Grade II* listed building includes an Adam-style ceiling on the 1st floor and a beautiful staircase with wrought-iron balustrade. Once home to the Pharmaceutical Society of Great Britain, it now houses an historical research institute.

name: Hanwell Community Centre
description: Victorian Grade II listed former Central London District School, known as the 'Cuckoo Schools', was 'home' to up to 1500 pauper children from inner London from 1857-1933.

name: Southwark Pupil Referral Unit
description: The Southwark Pupil Referral Unit is a new school for 11-14 year olds who have been excluded from mainstream schools or are at risk of exclusion. The aim is to reintegrate these students into mainstream education.

name: Thames Chase Forest Centre
description: Distinctive award-winning visitor centre of modern timber sustainable construction forming an A-frame building roofed with cedar shingles, attached to 17C listed barn - one of the best preserved in the London area.
address: Broadfields Farm, Pike Lane, Upminster, RM14 3NS

name: The Old Town Hall, Richmond
description: Red brick and Bath stone grand 'Elizabethan Renaissance' style building altered by war, political changes and reflecting Richmond's history. Overlooking the war memorial and the Thames.
address: Old Town Hall, Whittaker Avenue, Richmond, TW9 1TP

name: Ripple Greenway and the Lost Words Art Trail
description:
Ripple Greenway is a beautiful 14-acre linear park and art trail.  Home to Katy Hallett’s steel sculptures, inspired by Robert Macfarlane’s and Jackie Morris’ The Lost Words.
Wooden play and exercise equipment, picnic tables and benches.

name: Mount Pleasant Villas
description:
A contemporary remodelling of a Victorian terraced property with new features, fittings and materials
Architect-designed for open-plan family life
Space and daylight
Wrap-around rear extension relating to the garden
Conservation Area
address: 13 Mount Pleasant Villas, Finsbury Park, N4 3HB

name: Kimber House
description: Rear extension with internal reconfiguration of ground floor, internalisation of garage to create new living space.

name: Streatham Space Project
description: A neighborhood theatre, music, comedy venue using cultural events to bring people together. We pride ourselves on being a welcoming space celebrating everyone's creativity from children to emerging producers to experienced artists.

name: St Matthias
description: St Matthias' spire is easily visible as you approach Richmond Gate (Richmond Park). It is a Grade 2 listed church built between 1858-1862 with additions in 1884 & 1915. It was remodelled in the 1970s to provide both sacred & social space.

name: Darbishire Place (Peabody Whitechapel Estate)
description: New block of 13 homes which completes an ensemble of six housing blocks surrounding an internal courtyard.The façade complements the existing Victorian buildings by Henry Astley Darbishire. RIBA Award Winner & Stirling Prize shortlist 2015

name: Self-Guided Bexley Itinerary, by Open House
description: This self-guided walking itinerary has been created by the Open House team to explore exterior architecture in Bexley.

name: Workable
description: Situated within the Rogers Stirk Harbour + Partners designed buildings at IQL, Workable is a new approach to flexible working in Stratford that combines panoramic views over London with stylish interior design.

name: Chats Palace
description: Homerton Library (Chats Palace) is one of the UK's 660 Carnegie libraries. Designed for “betterment of the people of the East End"  its glass roof, leaded lights, marble floor and pillared frontage testify to the architect's eye for detail.

name: Studio Flox
description: Studio Flox at Watermans Art Centre is a combined arts centre. It is located in Brentford, England alongside the banks of the River Thames overlooking Kew Gardens in West London, England
address: WATERMANS PARK, 40A, HIGH STREET, BRENTFORD, TW8 0BB

name: New Museum of London, West Smithfield
description: The Museum of London is creating a new museum in the derelict General Market and adjacent post-war Poultry Market. For the first time in 20 years we are inviting the public to explore these spaces in historic and creative Smithfield.

name: Blackfriars Estate 150 year anniversary and Peabody history tour
description:
Join us for the 150 year anniversary of our Blackfriars Estate. We'll be running tours Saturday 4 September 2021 from 12.15 – 12.45pm, and 1.45 – 2.15pm.

The community event will run from 12pm - 3pm with speeches at 1pm.
address: Peabody Square, Blackfriars Road, Southwark London, SE1 8HU

name: Reuse and redevelopment: A walk in changing Southall
description: This walk through the most diverse of Ealing’s towns will consider the impact of development on the urban fabric and its communities.

name: Senate House
description: London’s tallest secular building when it opened as the HQ of the University of London and home to the Ministry of Information during WWII, this Grade II* listed landmark features Classicism and Art Deco elements.
address: University of London, Malet Street, WC1E 7HU

name: Case Study Terrace
description: Complete refurbishment of a modern terraced house. This house incorporates a galleried top-floor office space that overlooks a double-height, open-plan kitchen, living and dining space, with sleeping accomodation on the ground floor.

name: BAPS Shri Swaminarayan Mandir
description: Europe’s first traditional Hindu temple is a masterpiece of exquisite Indian craftsmanship. Using 5,000 tonnes of Italian and Indian marble and the finest Bulgarian limestone, it was hand-carved in India before being assembled in London.

name: Dorich House Museum
description: The former studio home of the sculptor Dora Gordine and her husband the Hon. Richard Hare, a scholar of Russian art and literature. 1930s house over four floors including a flat roof terrace and views of Richmond Park.
address: Dorich House Museum, 67 Kingston Vale, SW15 3RN

name: The City Churches: The Priory Church of St Bartholomew the Great
description: The oldest surviving church in the City of London founded in 1123. Originally part of an Augustinian Priory the church survived the Great Fire and the Blitz.

name: The Royal Society
description: A spectacular Grade I listed building designed by famed architect John Nash. Built in 1831, these former townhouses have undergone refurbishments throughout their history. The building is now home to the UK's national science academy.
address: The Royal Society, 6-9 Carlton House Terrace, SW1Y 5AG

name: Valence House
description: Grade II* listed 15C and later manor house with medieval moat. Recently discovered late 16C wall painting and impressive oak paneling. Evocative museum galleries that bring Barking & Dagenham's past alive.

name: The Wheelhouse
description: Listed building with unique 7-spoke Victorian waterwheel, the only daily working example in South London, originally used by Liberty's for rinsing printed silk, and now the home of a craft pottery and art studio.
address: Merton Abbey Mills, Merantun Way, SW19 2RD

name: Paxton Locher House
description: A unique modern courtyard house making brilliant use of a restricted site. A retractable glass roof gives wonderful natural light and opens the house to the sky in dry weather.

name: St Mary Magdalene
description: A historic living parish church, progressively shaped from the Tudor to the Edwardian period. St Mary's has recently undergone a major refurbishment and the newly restored windows recapture the original airiness of the C18 nave.

name: Self-guided Architecture Walk - Roehampton Lane
description: This self guided walk combines contemporary architecture with some historic survivals in Roehampton Village, via the famous Alton Estate, Roehampton University campus and Dover House Estate. Don’t forget to do the quiz!

name: St Michael and All Angels Church
description: James Maltby Bignall (1827-1885) worked in the practice of Sir George Gilbert Scott, the architect of St Pancras Station. The style of St Michael's is late Gothic Revival, in its size and height reminiscent of Northern European churches.

name: Modernism in Metroland
description: A walking tour of Stanmore's Art Deco and modernist homes, from the birth of Metroland to the post-war era.
address: Outside Stanmore tube station, London Road, Stanmore, HA7 4PD

name: Brandon Centre
description: West Kentish Town Conservation Area. Brandon Cadbury, (of the famous philanthropic chocolatiers) was so impressed with our founder and young peoples services he donated our building. As a thank you, we named the charity after him in 1984.
address: 26 Prince of Wales Road, Kentish Town, NW5 3LG

name: St Mary's Church, Battersea
description: Classic Grade I listed Georgian church with outstanding interior and monuments. Renovated 2019/20.

name: Guildhall Art Gallery
description: Houses the City of London's art collection, built over remains of London's 2C Roman amphitheatre. Façade uses Portland stone and Collyweston stone slates. Interior uses finishes of marble, American elm, damask and painted wall coverings.

name: Baker Street Complex
description: In 1863, Baker Street was one of the stations on the world's first subterranean metro line. The Metropolitan Railway developed the area around the station to incorporate offices and even residential flats. This tour explores that history.

name: Gresham College - Barnard's Inn Hall
description: Barnard's Inn dates back to the mid 13C. The hall contains three wooden bays dating from 15C with later linenfold wood panelling added in 1525. It was the Mercers' School and today is home to Gresham College offering FREE lectures for all.

name: St Peter-in-the-Forest Church & Community Centre
description: An 'Italian Romanesque' church set in Epping Forest, St Peter's was founded in 1840 and extended in 1887. The building underwent a major reordering throughout 2020 to save it from subsidence and create new community facilities.

name: Reuse, repurpose, reimagine: Buildings beyond their original identity
description: This walking tour will look at examples of how buildings have been altered to suit new uses. The tour considers what different scenarios lie behind this process of change and the design creativity that can emerge as a result

name: The Department Store
description: The Department Store is an award winning refurbishment of a dilapidated Edwardian building in Brixton, completed by Squire and Partners in 2017. The design was informed by the layers of history and existing fabric of the heritage building.
address: The Department Store, 248 Ferndale Road, SW9 8FR

name: Carshalton Water Tower and Historic Gardens
description: Early 18C Grade II listed building incorporating plunge bath with Delft tiles, orangery, saloon and pump chamber with part-restored water wheel. Hermitage and sham bridge in grounds.

name: St Luke's, Wimbledon Park
description: Architecturally consists of a nave with a gallery at the west end, chancel, north and south aisles. a chapel and south transept with a tower to the north. Three stained glass windows.
address: St. Lukes Church, Ryfold Road, SW19 8BZ

name: The City Churches: St Mary-le-Bow
description: Founded by William the Conqueror's Archbishop Lanfranc in 1080 (the significant crypt survives) St Mary-le-Bow was rebuilt, notably by Wren after the Great Fire and by Laurence King in 1964 after WWII destruction. Home of Bow Bells.

name: RC Church of St Mellitus (St Mellitus Organ Restoration Project)
description: A grandiose neo-classical building with impressive interior built in 1870-1, formerly New Court Congregational church and home to the Hunter pipe organ, built in memory of local WW1 soldiers and recently restored with Lottery funding.
address: Church of St Mellitus, Tollington Park, N4 3AG

name: City Hall
description: Home of the Mayor of London and London Assembly, an environmentally-aware building with innovative spiral ramp and fine views across London.
address: City Hall, The Queen's Walk, SE1 2AA

name: Verity-Jane Keefe, Living Together: The Becontree Collection Billboards
description: A walk across Becontree to view a new series of artworks installed on billboards & roadside locations, sharing some of the objects collected as part of Keefe’s long term project, Living Together, across the estate in its centenary year.
address: Becontree Station, Gale Street, Dagenham, RM9 4TP

name: Greenwich: Big picture, local focus
description: This walk will celebrate some of the famous parts of Greenwich but also look at recent local housing and buildings -- some controversial, some celebrated, as well as streets that are packed with small scale historical gems.

name: Twofold House
description: Large, openable glass-to-glass sliding doors sit seemingly precariously underneath a massive cantilever and a facetted roof rises up to meet a skylight at the highest point of this imposing extension in the Woodgrange Conservation Area.

name: Shepherds Bush Baptist Tabernacle WW1 Hall
description: The Tabernacle Memorial Hall is nestled behind the Tabernacle Church on Shepherds Bush road just off the green. Used as an office space for many years, it has been refurbished and restored into a complimentary health and wellbeing centre.
address: The Tabernacle Memorial Hall, Miller's Way, W6 7NH

name: All Saints Carshalton
description: 12C south aisle and former chancel. Blomfield nave, chancel, baptistry. Kempe glass, Bodley reredos and screen, spectacular Comper decorations, monuments and brasses, award-winning lighting scheme, fine modern benches.

name: Brentford Canal Toll House and Gauging Lock
description: Single-storey canal toll house (1911) where tolls were collected for passing through the lock. Grand Junction Canal connected the Thames at Brentford to the Industrial Midlands in 1794 at the height of the industrial revolution.
address: Access off High Street, Brentford, TW8 8EE

name: Lamorbey House
description: World-renowned Rose Bruford drama college with recent additions and landscaping to provide contemporary state of the art facilities. Site also includes Grade II listed Lamorbey Park Mansion – a rare survivor of Sidcup's Georgian houses.
address: Lamorbey Park, Burnt Oak Lane,, Sidcup, DA15 9DF

name: White City in the 21st Century
description: External walking tour of the White City redevelopment. Includes new build shopping and housing.  Imperial College White City Campus and the reuse of the BBC Television Centre and Media Village. This is a major redevlopment of the area
address: Shepherds Bush Station, Uxbridge Road, W12 7FD

name: Bunhill Heat and Power Energy Centre
description: A district heating energy centre providing low carbon heating to around 1,300 properties.

name: Abbey Mills Pumping Station
description: Abbey Mills pumping station 'A', built by engineer Joseph Bazalgette, Edmund Cooper and architect Charles Driver. Built between 1865 and 1868 it has been described as the cathedral of sewage.

name: City of Westminster Archives Centre
description: Modern red brick building purpose-built to house the City of Westminster's historic records. Opportunity to visit the conservation studio and see treasures of the archives.

name: Parish Church of St Anne
description: Grade II* listed, originally built as a chapel under the patronage of Queen Anne in 1714 and subsequently enlarged. Many notable memorials including to scientist William Jackson Hooker and tombs of Thomas Gainsborough and Johan Zoffany.

name: Christ Church, Streatham
description: Grade I listed pioneering brick polychromy. Designed with early Christian, Italian, Ottoman, Alhambran, Mamluk, Sevillean and Ancient Egyptian influences with fine mosaics and stained glass by Crane, Bentley. Lee and Hayward.

name: Hanwell Flight of Locks & Three Bridges
description: Flight of locks and side ponds at Hanwell is a Scheduled  Monument. Three Bridges is a unique stacked intersection of road, rail and canal and Brunel's last major railway project. Walks led by knowledgeable enthusiasts.
address: The Fox public house, Green Lane, W7 2PJ

name: UCL Pearl
description: UCL PEARL is a brand new building designed to be a laboratory that can "house the world" so that we can create different environments from around the world for experiments about people and the environment around them.
address: UCL PEARL, Yew Tree Avenue, RM10 7FN

name: Millennium Mills
description: Built in the early 20C by flour company Spillers, the Art Deco landmark has stood vacant since the decline of the docks as a working port in the 1980s.
address: North Woolwich Road, Royal Docks, E16 1UR

name: The Mysterious Black Tudors - Family Trail
description: Celebrate Open House Festival 2021 with this fun and interactive family event about Britain's forgotten history of the Black Tudors.

name: The Mildmay Club
description: A rare example of a large purpose built metropolitan working men’s club with over 100 years of history. A once dignified building, revival Queen Anne style in the late-Victorian period, Grade II listed in 2019.

name: Gasholder Park
description: Gasholder Park is a tranquil public space set within a carefully restored guide frame of a Victorian gasholder in the heart of King's Cross. The pavilion frames a central garden with a stunning mirror-polished stainless steel colonnade.
address: Gasholder Park, Regent’s Canal Towpath, Kings Cross, N1C 4AB

name: Waterloo City Farm
description: Feilden Fowles is situated within a walled garden on a discreet corner of Waterloo City Farm. Feilden Fowles designed the farm and its office and educational spaces, which is run by two charities: Jamie’s Farm and the Oasis Community Hub.

name: St John the Divine
description: St John’s has a wide nave approached via a narthex formed under the gallery running the width of the west end.  East of the nave is a chancel flanked to the south by the Lady Chapel and to the north by the organ chamber with loft over.

name: Peter Jones
description: Grade II* listed building, involving complex mix of new build and restoration. Britain's first ever curtain walling and listed features such as spiral staircase. Sloane Room has one of best views over Chelsea. RIBA Award Winner 2005.

name: Woolwich Heritage Action Zone
description: Come and pick up a self-guided tour of Woolwich, learn more about the Woolwich Heritage Action Zone and 'Meet the Collection', a chance to see some of the collection from the Borough's Museum and Archive collection.

name: St Mary Magdalene Church & Nature Reserve
description: Grade I listed 12C church, with London's largest churchyard and one of the best-preserved Norman archways in the country, as well as other interesting features, including an anchorite's cell and 750-year-old wall paintings.
address: East Ham,  High Street South/ Norman Road, E6 3PG

name: Caledonian Park: Park Walking Tour
description: Tour of the park and local area, discover how Copenhagen Fields became Caledonian Park and how diplomacy gave way to debauchery and agitation and then butchery and commerce.

name: Jubilee Market
description: The Jubilee Hall, which houses the Jubilee Market, was built in 1904 in the heart of Covent Garden and gained Grade 2 listed status in 1980. The market was officially re opened after renovation by Queen Elizabeth II in 1987.
address: 1  Tavistock Place, The Piazza, Covent Garden, WC2E 8BD, WC2E 8BD

name: Van Gogh House London
description: The carefully renovated Van Gogh House seeks to share its story and inspire a new generation of artists through Van Gogh’s London story. The house curates a dynamic programme of events anchored in the artist’s practice and local heritage.

name: Lansbury Lawrence Primary School
description: Lansbury Lawrence (formally Susan Lawrence and Elizabeth Lansbury) opened in the 1951 Festival of Britain as a showpiece of the Live Architecture exhibition in the Lansbury Estate. An interesting mid-century design with original features.

name: Writing's on the Wall
description: 'The Writing's on the Wall' - a celebration of the street art of East London. Join Mr Londoner, aka former museum director and Blue Badge guide Antony Robbins, to discover the best street art in Shoreditch and beyond.

name: A River's Tale. A guided walk along the Thames Path
description: For about an hour and a half we will walk along the Thames Path from Millennium Bridge  finishing at the old Billingsgate Fish Market along the way learning of the prosperity, power, prestige and plague this great river has brought us

name: Kingston Library, Museum and Art Gallery
description: Adjoining Grade II listed Carnegie-funded library, museum and art gallery. Museum holdings range from ceramics to topographical drawings, including the collection left by Eadweard Muybridge, a native of Kingston and photographic pioneer.
address: Wheatfield Way, Kingston upon Thames, KT1 2PS

name: The Sponge
description: An imaginative solution to today's contrasting needs of open spaces and privacy. A large open plan ground floor is carved by joinery items and a wooden slatted box leading to the basement. Natural light filters through the whole house.

name: The Brentford Gallery
